  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What languages and frameworks are used to code?",
  "response": "The programming languages and frameworks used to code depend on the specific project, application, or platform being developed. Here\u2019s a general overview of popular languages and frameworks across different domains:\n\n### **Programming Languages**\n1. **JavaScript** - Primarily used for web development (front-end and back-end with Node.js).\n2. **Python** - Popular for web development, data science, machine learning, and scripting.\n3. **Java** - Widely used for enterprise applications, Android development, and large-scale systems.\n4. **C#** - Used for Windows applications, game development (Unity), and enterprise software.\n5. **C++** - Common in game development, system/software development, and performance-critical applications.\n6. **PHP** - Mainly for server-side web development.\n7. **Ruby** - Known for web development and scripting.\n8. **Swift** - Used for iOS and macOS app development.\n9. **Go (Golang)** - Popular for cloud-based applications, microservices, and scalable systems.\n10. **Kotlin** - Used for Android development and server-side applications.\n11. **TypeScript** - A superset of JavaScript, used for large-scale web applications.\n12. **Rust** - Gaining popularity for system-level programming due to its safety and performance.\n13. **SQL** - For managing and querying relational databases.\n\n### **Front-End Frameworks (Web Development)**\n1. **React.js** - A JavaScript library for building user interfaces (maintained by Facebook).\n2. **Angular** - A TypeScript-based framework for building dynamic web apps (maintained by Google).\n3. **Vue.js** - A progressive JavaScript framework for building UIs.\n4. **Svelte** - A modern framework for building fast, lightweight web applications.\n5. **Bootstrap** - A CSS framework for responsive design and pre-built components.\n\n### **Back-End Frameworks**\n1. **Node.js** - A JavaScript runtime for building server-side applications.\n2. **Express.js** - A lightweight framework for Node.js.\n3. **Django** - A Python framework for rapid web development.\n4. **Flask** - A lightweight Python framework for microservices and small apps.\n5. **Ruby on Rails** - A Ruby framework for full-stack web development.\n6. **Spring Boot** - A Java framework for building enterprise-level applications.\n7. **Laravel** - A PHP framework for web development.\n8. **ASP.NET Core** - A C# framework for building modern web applications and APIs.\n9. **FastAPI** - A modern Python framework for building APIs.\n\n### **Mobile Development Frameworks**\n1. **Flutter** - A Google framework for building cross-platform apps (iOS and Android) using Dart.\n2. **React Native** - A framework for building cross-platform apps using JavaScript.\n3. **Xamarin** - A C# framework for cross-platform mobile development.\n\n### **Data Science and Machine Learning**\n1. **TensorFlow** - A Python-based framework for machine learning and deep learning.\n2. **PyTorch** - A Python framework for machine learning, popular in research.\n3. **Scikit-learn** - A Python library for machine learning and data analysis.\n4. **Pandas** - A Python library for data manipulation and analysis.\n5. **NumPy** - A Python library for numerical computations.\n\n### **Game Development**\n1. **Unity** - A C#-based engine for 2D and 3D game development.\n2. **Unreal Engine** - A C++-based engine for high-end game development.\n3. **Godot** - An open-source engine for 2D and 3D game development.\n\n### **Other Frameworks**\n1. **GraphQL** - A query language for APIs, often used with Apollo or Relay.\n2. **Redis** - A caching and in-memory data store.\n3. **Docker** - A platform for containerization and deployment.\n4. **Kubernetes** - An orchestration platform for managing containers.\n\nThe choice of language and framework depends on the project's requirements, the development team's expertise, and the desired performance and scalability.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
